309 // Helpers: Bit manipulation
310 static inline bool ImIsPowerOfTwo(int v)
311 {
312  return v != 0 && (v & (v - 1)) == 0;
313 }
314 static inline bool ImIsPowerOfTwo(ImU64 v)
315 {
316  return v != 0 && (v & (v - 1)) == 0;
317 }
318 static inline int ImUpperPowerOfTwo(int v)
319 {
320  v--; v |= v >> 1; v |= v >> 2; v |= v >> 4; v |= v >> 8; v |= v >> 16; v++; return v;
321 }

360 // Helpers: ImVec2/ImVec4 operators
361 // We are keeping those disabled by default so they don't leak in user space, to allow user enabling implicit cast operators between ImVec2 and their own types (using IM_VEC2_CLASS_EXTRA etc.)
362 // We unfortunately don't have a unary- operator for ImVec2 because this would needs to be defined inside the class itself.
363 #ifdef IMGUI_DEFINE_MATH_OPERATORS
364 IM_MSVC_RUNTIME_CHECKS_OFF
365 static inline ImVec2 operator*(const ImVec2 &lhs, const float rhs)
366 {
367  return ImVec2(lhs.x * rhs, lhs.y * rhs);
368 }
369 static inline ImVec2 operator/(const ImVec2 &lhs, const float rhs)
370 {
371  return ImVec2(lhs.x / rhs, lhs.y / rhs);
372 }
373 static inline ImVec2 operator+(const ImVec2 &lhs, const ImVec2 &rhs)
374 {
375  return ImVec2(lhs.x + rhs.x, lhs.y + rhs.y);
376 }
377 static inline ImVec2 operator-(const ImVec2 &lhs, const ImVec2 &rhs)
378 {
379  return ImVec2(lhs.x - rhs.x, lhs.y - rhs.y);
380 }
381 static inline ImVec2 operator*(const ImVec2 &lhs, const ImVec2 &rhs)
382 {
383  return ImVec2(lhs.x * rhs.x, lhs.y * rhs.y);
384 }
385 static inline ImVec2 operator/(const ImVec2 &lhs, const ImVec2 &rhs)
386 {
387  return ImVec2(lhs.x / rhs.x, lhs.y / rhs.y);
388 }
389 static inline ImVec2 &operator*=(ImVec2 &lhs, const float rhs)
390 {
391  lhs.x *= rhs; lhs.y *= rhs; return lhs;
392 }
393 static inline ImVec2 &operator/=(ImVec2 &lhs, const float rhs)
394 {
395  lhs.x /= rhs; lhs.y /= rhs; return lhs;
396 }
397 static inline ImVec2 &operator+=(ImVec2 &lhs, const ImVec2 &rhs)
398 {
399  lhs.x += rhs.x; lhs.y += rhs.y; return lhs;
400 }
401 static inline ImVec2 &operator-=(ImVec2 &lhs, const ImVec2 &rhs)
402 {
403  lhs.x -= rhs.x; lhs.y -= rhs.y; return lhs;
404 }
405 static inline ImVec2 &operator*=(ImVec2 &lhs, const ImVec2 &rhs)
406 {
407  lhs.x *= rhs.x; lhs.y *= rhs.y; return lhs;
408 }
409 static inline ImVec2 &operator/=(ImVec2 &lhs, const ImVec2 &rhs)
410 {
411  lhs.x /= rhs.x; lhs.y /= rhs.y; return lhs;
412 }
413 static inline ImVec4 operator+(const ImVec4 &lhs, const ImVec4 &rhs)
414 {
415  return ImVec4(lhs.x + rhs.x, lhs.y + rhs.y, lhs.z + rhs.z, lhs.w + rhs.w);
416 }
417 static inline ImVec4 operator-(const ImVec4 &lhs, const ImVec4 &rhs)
418 {
419  return ImVec4(lhs.x - rhs.x, lhs.y - rhs.y, lhs.z - rhs.z, lhs.w - rhs.w);
420 }
421 static inline ImVec4 operator*(const ImVec4 &lhs, const ImVec4 &rhs)
422 {
423  return ImVec4(lhs.x * rhs.x, lhs.y * rhs.y, lhs.z * rhs.z, lhs.w * rhs.w);
424 }
425 IM_MSVC_RUNTIME_CHECKS_RESTORE
426 #endif

465 // Helpers: Maths

467 // - Wrapper for standard libs functions. (Note that imgui_demo.cpp does _not_ use them to keep the code easy to copy)
468 #ifndef IMGUI_DISABLE_DEFAULT_MATH_FUNCTIONS

478 #define ImCeil(X) ceilf(X)
479 static inline float ImPow(float x, float y)
480 {
481  return powf(x, y);
482 } // DragBehaviorT/SliderBehaviorT uses ImPow with either float/double and need the precision
483 static inline double ImPow(double x, double y)
484 {
485  return pow(x, y);
486 }
487 static inline float ImLog(float x)
488 {
489  return logf(x);
490 } // DragBehaviorT/SliderBehaviorT uses ImLog with either float/double and need the precision
491 static inline double ImLog(double x)
492 {
493  return log(x);
494 }
495 static inline int ImAbs(int x)
496 {
497  return x < 0 ? -x : x;
498 }
499 static inline float ImAbs(float x)
500 {
501  return fabsf(x);
502 }
503 static inline double ImAbs(double x)
504 {
505  return fabs(x);
506 }
507 static inline float ImSign(float x)
508 {
509  return (x < 0.0f) ? -1.0f : ((x > 0.0f) ? 1.0f : 0.0f);
510 } // Sign operator - returns -1, 0 or 1 based on sign of argument
511 static inline double ImSign(double x)
512 {
513  return (x < 0.0) ? -1.0 : ((x > 0.0) ? 1.0 : 0.0);
514 }
515 #ifdef IMGUI_ENABLE_SSE
516 static inline float ImRsqrt(float x)
517 {
518  return _mm_cvtss_f32(_mm_rsqrt_ss(_mm_set_ss(x)));
519 }
520 #else
521 static inline float ImRsqrt(float x)
522 {
523  return 1.0f / sqrtf(x);
524 }
525 #endif
526 static inline double ImRsqrt(double x)
527 {
528  return 1.0 / sqrt(x);
529 }
530 #endif
531 // - ImMin/ImMax/ImClamp/ImLerp/ImSwap are used by widgets which support variety of types: signed/unsigned int/long long float/double
532 // (Exceptionally using templates here but we could also redefine them for those types)
533 template<typename T> static inline T ImMin(T lhs, T rhs)
534 {
535  return lhs < rhs ? lhs : rhs;
536 }
537 template<typename T> static inline T ImMax(T lhs, T rhs)
538 {
539  return lhs >= rhs ? lhs : rhs;
540 }
541 template<typename T> static inline T ImClamp(T v, T mn, T mx)
542 {
543  return (v < mn) ? mn : (v > mx) ? mx : v;
544 }
545 template<typename T> static inline T ImLerp(T a, T b, float t)
546 {
547  return (T)(a + (b - a) * t);
548 }
549 template<typename T> static inline void ImSwap(T &a, T &b)
550 {
551  T tmp = a; a = b; b = tmp;
552 }
553 template<typename T> static inline T ImAddClampOverflow(T a, T b, T mn, T mx)
554 {
555  if (b < 0 && (a < mn - b)) return mn; if (b > 0 && (a > mx - b)) return mx; return a + b;
556 }
557 template<typename T> static inline T ImSubClampOverflow(T a, T b, T mn, T mx)
558 {
559  if (b > 0 && (a < mn + b)) return mn; if (b < 0 && (a > mx + b)) return mx; return a - b;
560 }
561 // - Misc maths helpers
562 static inline ImVec2 ImMin(const ImVec2 &lhs, const ImVec2 &rhs)
563 {
564  return ImVec2(lhs.x < rhs.x ? lhs.x : rhs.x, lhs.y < rhs.y ? lhs.y : rhs.y);
565 }
566 static inline ImVec2 ImMax(const ImVec2 &lhs, const ImVec2 &rhs)
567 {
568  return ImVec2(lhs.x >= rhs.x ? lhs.x : rhs.x, lhs.y >= rhs.y ? lhs.y : rhs.y);
569 }
570 static inline ImVec2 ImClamp(const ImVec2 &v, const ImVec2 &mn, ImVec2 mx)
571 {
572  return ImVec2((v.x < mn.x) ? mn.x : (v.x > mx.x) ? mx.x : v.x, (v.y < mn.y) ? mn.y : (v.y > mx.y) ? mx.y : v.y);
573 }
574 static inline ImVec2 ImLerp(const ImVec2 &a, const ImVec2 &b, float t)
575 {
576  return ImVec2(a.x + (b.x - a.x) * t, a.y + (b.y - a.y) * t);
577 }
578 static inline ImVec2 ImLerp(const ImVec2 &a, const ImVec2 &b, const ImVec2 &t)
579 {
580  return ImVec2(a.x + (b.x - a.x) * t.x, a.y + (b.y - a.y) * t.y);
581 }
582 static inline ImVec4 ImLerp(const ImVec4 &a, const ImVec4 &b, float t)
583 {
584  return ImVec4(a.x + (b.x - a.x) * t, a.y + (b.y - a.y) * t, a.z + (b.z - a.z) * t, a.w + (b.w - a.w) * t);
585 }
586 static inline float ImSaturate(float f)
587 {
588  return (f < 0.0f) ? 0.0f : (f > 1.0f) ? 1.0f : f;
589 }
590 static inline float ImLengthSqr(const ImVec2 &lhs)
591 {
592  return (lhs.x * lhs.x) + (lhs.y * lhs.y);
593 }
594 static inline float ImLengthSqr(const ImVec4 &lhs)
595 {
596  return (lhs.x * lhs.x) + (lhs.y * lhs.y) + (lhs.z * lhs.z) + (lhs.w * lhs.w);
597 }
598 static inline float ImInvLength(const ImVec2 &lhs, float fail_value)
599 {
600  float d = (lhs.x * lhs.x) + (lhs.y * lhs.y); if (d > 0.0f) return ImRsqrt(d); return fail_value;
601 }
602 static inline float ImFloor(float f)
603 {
604  return (float)(int)(f);
605 }
606 static inline float ImFloorSigned(float f)
607 {
608  return (float)((f >= 0 || (int)f == f) ? (int)f : (int)f - 1);
609 } // Decent replacement for floorf()
610 static inline ImVec2 ImFloor(const ImVec2 &v)
611 {
612  return ImVec2((float)(int)(v.x), (float)(int)(v.y));
613 }
614 static inline int ImModPositive(int a, int b)
615 {
616  return (a + b) % b;
617 }
618 static inline float ImDot(const ImVec2 &a, const ImVec2 &b)
619 {
620  return a.x * b.x + a.y * b.y;
621 }
622 static inline ImVec2 ImRotate(const ImVec2 &v, float cos_a, float sin_a)
623 {
624  return ImVec2(v.x * cos_a - v.y * sin_a, v.x * sin_a + v.y * cos_a);
625 }
626 static inline float ImLinearSweep(float current, float target, float speed)
627 {
628  if (current < target) return ImMin(current + speed, target); if (current > target) return ImMax(current - speed, target); return current;
629 }
630 static inline ImVec2 ImMul(const ImVec2 &lhs, const ImVec2 &rhs)
631 {

685 // Helper: ImRect (2D axis aligned bounding-box)
686 // NB: we can't rely on ImVec2 math operators being available here!
687 struct IMGUI_API ImRect
688 {
689  ImVec2 Min; // Upper-left
690  ImVec2 Max; // Lower-right
691 
692  ImRect() : Min(0.0f, 0.0f), Max(0.0f, 0.0f)
693  {
694  }
695  ImRect(const ImVec2 &min, const ImVec2 &max) : Min(min), Max(max)
696  {
697  }
698  ImRect(const ImVec4 &v) : Min(v.x, v.y), Max(v.z, v.w)
699  {
700  }
701  ImRect(float x1, float y1, float x2, float y2) : Min(x1, y1), Max(x2, y2)
702  {
703  }
704 
705  ImVec2 GetCenter() const
706  {
707  return ImVec2((Min.x + Max.x) * 0.5f, (Min.y + Max.y) * 0.5f);
708  }
709  ImVec2 GetSize() const
710  {
711  return ImVec2(Max.x - Min.x, Max.y - Min.y);
712  }
713  float GetWidth() const
714  {
715  return Max.x - Min.x;
716  }
717  float GetHeight() const
718  {
719  return Max.y - Min.y;
720  }
721  float GetArea() const
722  {
723  return (Max.x - Min.x) * (Max.y - Min.y);
724  }
725  ImVec2 GetTL() const
726  {
727  return Min;
728  } // Top-left
729  ImVec2 GetTR() const
730  {
731  return ImVec2(Max.x, Min.y);
732  } // Top-right
733  ImVec2 GetBL() const
734  {
735  return ImVec2(Min.x, Max.y);
736  } // Bottom-left
737  ImVec2 GetBR() const
738  {
739  return Max;
740  } // Bottom-right
741  bool Contains(const ImVec2 &p) const
742  {
743  return p.x >= Min.x && p.y >= Min.y && p.x < Max.x &&p.y < Max.y;
744  }
745  bool Contains(const ImRect &r) const
746  {
747  return r.Min.x >= Min.x && r.Min.y >= Min.y && r.Max.x <= Max.x && r.Max.y <= Max.y;
748  }
749  bool Overlaps(const ImRect &r) const
750  {
751  return r.Min.y < Max.y &&r.Max.y > Min.y && r.Min.x < Max.x &&r.Max.x > Min.x;
752  }
753  void Add(const ImVec2 &p)
754  {
755  if (Min.x > p.x) Min.x = p.x; if (Min.y > p.y) Min.y = p.y; if (Max.x < p.x) Max.x = p.x; if (Max.y < p.y) Max.y = p.y;
756  }
757  void Add(const ImRect &r)
758  {
759  if (Min.x > r.Min.x) Min.x = r.Min.x; if (Min.y > r.Min.y) Min.y = r.Min.y; if (Max.x < r.Max.x) Max.x = r.Max.x; if (Max.y < r.Max.y) Max.y = r.Max.y;
760  }
761  void Expand(const float amount)
762  {
763  Min.x -= amount; Min.y -= amount; Max.x += amount; Max.y += amount;
764  }
765  void Expand(const ImVec2 &amount)
766  {
767  Min.x -= amount.x; Min.y -= amount.y; Max.x += amount.x; Max.y += amount.y;
768  }
769  void Translate(const ImVec2 &d)
770  {
771  Min.x += d.x; Min.y += d.y; Max.x += d.x; Max.y += d.y;
772  }
773  void TranslateX(float dx)
774  {
775  Min.x += dx; Max.x += dx;
776  }
777  void TranslateY(float dy)
778  {
779  Min.y += dy; Max.y += dy;
780  }
781  void ClipWith(const ImRect &r)
782  {
783  Min = ImMax(Min, r.Min); Max = ImMin(Max, r.Max);
784  } // Simple version, may lead to an inverted rectangle, which is fine for Contains/Overlaps test but not for display.
785  void ClipWithFull(const ImRect &r)
786  {
787  Min = ImClamp(Min, r.Min, r.Max); Max = ImClamp(Max, r.Min, r.Max);
788  } // Full version, ensure both points are fully clipped.
789  void Floor()
790  {
791  Min.x = IM_FLOOR(Min.x); Min.y = IM_FLOOR(Min.y); Max.x = IM_FLOOR(Max.x); Max.y = IM_FLOOR(Max.y);
792  }
793  bool IsInverted() const
794  {
795  return Min.x > Max.x || Min.y > Max.y;
796  }
797  ImVec4 ToVec4() const
798  {
799  return ImVec4(Min.x, Min.y, Max.x, Max.y);
800  }
801 };

804 // Helper: ImBitArray
805 inline bool ImBitArrayTestBit(const ImU32 *arr, int n)
806 {
807  ImU32 mask = (ImU32)1 << (n & 31); return (arr[n >> 5] & mask) != 0;
808 }
809 inline void ImBitArrayClearBit(ImU32 *arr, int n)
810 {
811  ImU32 mask = (ImU32)1 << (n & 31); arr[n >> 5] &= ~mask;
812 }
813 inline void ImBitArraySetBit(ImU32 *arr, int n)
814 {
815  ImU32 mask = (ImU32)1 << (n & 31); arr[n >> 5] |= mask;
816 }
817 inline void ImBitArraySetBitRange(ImU32 *arr, int n, int n2) // Works on range [n..n2)
818 {
819  n2--;
820  while (n <= n2)
821  {
822  int a_mod = (n & 31);
823  int b_mod = (n2 > (n | 31) ? 31 : (n2 & 31)) + 1;
824  ImU32 mask = (ImU32)(((ImU64)1 << b_mod) - 1) & ~(ImU32)(((ImU64)1 << a_mod) - 1);
825  arr[n >> 5] |= mask;
826  n = (n + 32) & ~31;
827  }
828 }
829 
830 // Helper: ImBitArray class (wrapper over ImBitArray functions)
831 // Store 1-bit per value.
832 template<int BITCOUNT>
833 struct IMGUI_API ImBitArray
834 {
835  ImU32 Storage[(BITCOUNT + 31) >> 5];
836  ImBitArray()
837  {
838  ClearAllBits();
839  }
840  void ClearAllBits()
841  {
842  memset(Storage, 0, sizeof(Storage));
843  }
844  void SetAllBits()
845  {
846  memset(Storage, 255, sizeof(Storage));
847  }
848  bool TestBit(int n) const
849  {
850  IM_ASSERT(n < BITCOUNT); return ImBitArrayTestBit(Storage, n);
851  }
852  void SetBit(int n)
853  {
854  IM_ASSERT(n < BITCOUNT); ImBitArraySetBit(Storage, n);
855  }
856  void ClearBit(int n)
857  {
858  IM_ASSERT(n < BITCOUNT); ImBitArrayClearBit(Storage, n);
859  }
860  void SetBitRange(int n, int n2)
861  {
862  ImBitArraySetBitRange(Storage, n, n2);
863  } // Works on range [n..n2)
864 };
865 
866 // Helper: ImBitVector
867 // Store 1-bit per value.
868 struct IMGUI_API ImBitVector
869 {
870  ImVector<ImU32> Storage;
871  void Create(int sz)
872  {
873  Storage.resize((sz + 31) >> 5); memset(Storage.Data, 0, (size_t)Storage.Size * sizeof(Storage.Data[0]));
874  }
875  void Clear()
876  {
877  Storage.clear();
878  }
879  bool TestBit(int n) const
880  {
881  IM_ASSERT(n < (Storage.Size << 5)); return ImBitArrayTestBit(Storage.Data, n);
882  }
883  void SetBit(int n)
884  {
885  IM_ASSERT(n < (Storage.Size << 5)); ImBitArraySetBit(Storage.Data, n);
886  }
887  void ClearBit(int n)
888  {
889  IM_ASSERT(n < (Storage.Size << 5)); ImBitArrayClearBit(Storage.Data, n);
890  }
891 };

893 // Helper: ImSpan<>
894 // Pointing to a span of data we don't own.
895 template<typename T>
896 struct ImSpan
897 {
898  T *Data;
899  T *DataEnd;
900 
901  // Constructors, destructor
902  inline ImSpan()
903  {
904  Data = DataEnd = NULL;
905  }
906  inline ImSpan(T *data, int size)
907  {
908  Data = data; DataEnd = data + size;
909  }
910  inline ImSpan(T *data, T *data_end)
911  {
912  Data = data; DataEnd = data_end;
913  }
914 
915  inline void set(T *data, int size)
916  {
917  Data = data; DataEnd = data + size;
918  }
919  inline void set(T *data, T *data_end)
920  {
921  Data = data; DataEnd = data_end;
922  }
923  inline int size() const
924  {
925  return (int)(ptrdiff_t)(DataEnd - Data);
926  }
927  inline int size_in_bytes() const
928  {
929  return (int)(ptrdiff_t)(DataEnd - Data) * (int)sizeof(T);
930  }
931  inline T &operator[](int i)
932  {
933  T *p = Data + i; IM_ASSERT(p >= Data && p < DataEnd); return *p;
934  }
935  inline const T &operator[](int i) const
936  {
937  const T *p = Data + i; IM_ASSERT(p >= Data && p < DataEnd); return *p;
938  }
939 
940  inline T *begin()
941  {
942  return Data;
943  }
944  inline const T *begin() const
945  {
946  return Data;
947  }
948  inline T *end()
949  {
950  return DataEnd;
951  }
952  inline const T *end() const
953  {
954  return DataEnd;
955  }
956 
957  // Utilities
958  inline int index_from_ptr(const T *it) const
959  {
960  IM_ASSERT(it >= Data && it < DataEnd); const ptrdiff_t off = it - Data; return (int)off;
961  }
962 };

964 // Helper: ImSpanAllocator<>
965 // Facilitate storing multiple chunks into a single large block (the "arena")
966 // - Usage: call Reserve() N times, allocate GetArenaSizeInBytes() worth, pass it to SetArenaBasePtr(), call GetSpan() N times to retrieve the aligned ranges.
967 template<int CHUNKS>
968 struct ImSpanAllocator
969 {
970  char *BasePtr;
971  int CurrOff;
972  int CurrIdx;
973  int Offsets[CHUNKS];
974  int Sizes[CHUNKS];
975 
976  ImSpanAllocator()
977  {
978  memset(this, 0, sizeof(*this));
979  }
980  inline void Reserve(int n, size_t sz, int a = 4)
981  {
982  IM_ASSERT(n == CurrIdx && n < CHUNKS); CurrOff = IM_MEMALIGN(CurrOff, a); Offsets[n] = CurrOff; Sizes[n] = (int)sz; CurrIdx++; CurrOff += (int)sz;
983  }
984  inline int GetArenaSizeInBytes()
985  {
986  return CurrOff;
987  }
988  inline void SetArenaBasePtr(void *base_ptr)
989  {
990  BasePtr = (char *)base_ptr;
991  }
992  inline void *GetSpanPtrBegin(int n)
993  {
994  IM_ASSERT(n >= 0 && n < CHUNKS &&CurrIdx == CHUNKS); return (void *)(BasePtr + Offsets[n]);
995  }
996  inline void *GetSpanPtrEnd(int n)
997  {
998  IM_ASSERT(n >= 0 && n < CHUNKS &&CurrIdx == CHUNKS); return (void *)(BasePtr + Offsets[n] + Sizes[n]);
999  }
1000  template<typename T>
1001  inline void GetSpan(int n, ImSpan<T> *span)
1002  {
1003  span->set((T *)GetSpanPtrBegin(n), (T *)GetSpanPtrEnd(n));
1004  }
1005 };
1006 
1007 // Helper: ImPool<>
1008 // Basic keyed storage for contiguous instances, slow/amortized insertion, O(1) indexable, O(Log N) queries by ID over a dense/hot buffer,
1009 // Honor constructor/destructor. Add/remove invalidate all pointers. Indexes have the same lifetime as the associated object.
1010 typedef int ImPoolIdx;
1011 template<typename T>
1012 struct IMGUI_API ImPool
1013 {
1014  ImVector<T> Buf; // Contiguous data
1015  ImGuiStorage Map; // ID->Index
1016  ImPoolIdx FreeIdx; // Next free idx to use
1017  ImPoolIdx AliveCount; // Number of active/alive items (for display purpose)
1018 
1019  ImPool()
1020  {
1021  FreeIdx = AliveCount = 0;
1022  }
1023  ~ImPool()
1024  {
1025  Clear();
1026  }
1027  T *GetByKey(ImGuiID key)
1028  {
1029  int idx = Map.GetInt(key, -1); return (idx != -1) ? &Buf[idx] : NULL;
1030  }
1031  T *GetByIndex(ImPoolIdx n)
1032  {
1033  return &Buf[n];
1034  }
1035  ImPoolIdx GetIndex(const T *p) const
1036  {
1037  IM_ASSERT(p >= Buf.Data && p < Buf.Data + Buf.Size); return (ImPoolIdx)(p - Buf.Data);
1038  }
1039  T *GetOrAddByKey(ImGuiID key)
1040  {
1041  int *p_idx = Map.GetIntRef(key, -1); if (*p_idx != -1) return &Buf[*p_idx]; *p_idx = FreeIdx; return Add();
1042  }
1043  bool Contains(const T *p) const
1044  {
1045  return (p >= Buf.Data && p < Buf.Data + Buf.Size);
1046  }
1047  void Clear()
1048  {
1049  for (int n = 0; n < Map.Data.Size; n++)
1050  {
1051  int idx = Map.Data[n].val_i; if (idx != -1) Buf[idx].~T();
1052  } Map.Clear(); Buf.clear(); FreeIdx = AliveCount = 0;
1053  }
1054  T *Add()
1055  {
1056  int idx = FreeIdx; if (idx == Buf.Size)
1057  {
1058  Buf.resize(Buf.Size + 1); FreeIdx++;
1059  }
1060  else
1061  {
1062  FreeIdx = *(int *)&Buf[idx];
1063  } IM_PLACEMENT_NEW(&Buf[idx]) T(); AliveCount++; return &Buf[idx];
1064  }
1065  void Remove(ImGuiID key, const T *p)
1066  {
1067  Remove(key, GetIndex(p));
1068  }
1069  void Remove(ImGuiID key, ImPoolIdx idx)
1070  {
1071  Buf[idx].~T(); *(int *)&Buf[idx] = FreeIdx; FreeIdx = idx; Map.SetIntUniform(key, -1); AliveCount--;
1072  }
1073  void Reserve(int capacity)
1074  {
1075  Buf.reserve(capacity); Map.Data.reserve(capacity);
1076  }
1077 
1078  // To iterate a ImPool: for (int n = 0; n < pool.GetMapSize(); n++) if (T* t = pool.TryGetMapData(n)) { ... }
1079  // Can be avoided if you know .Remove() has never been called on the pool, or AliveCount == GetMapSize()
1080  int GetAliveCount() const
1081  {
1082  return AliveCount;
1083  } // Number of active/alive items in the pool (for display purpose)
1084  int GetBufSize() const
1085  {
1086  return Buf.Size;
1087  }
1088  int GetMapSize() const
1089  {
1090  return Map.Data.Size;
1091  } // It is the map we need iterate to find valid items, since we don't have "alive" storage anywhere
1092  T *TryGetMapData(ImPoolIdx n)
1093  {
1094  int idx = Map.Data[n].val_i; if (idx == -1) return NULL; return GetByIndex(idx);
1095  }
1096 #ifndef IMGUI_DISABLE_OBSOLETE_FUNCTIONS
1097  int GetSize()
1098  {
1099  return GetMapSize();
1100  } // For ImPlot: should use GetMapSize() from (IMGUI_VERSION_NUM >= 18304)
1101 #endif
1102 };
1103 
1104 // Helper: ImChunkStream<>
1105 // Build and iterate a contiguous stream of variable-sized structures.
1106 // This is used by Settings to store persistent data while reducing allocation count.
1107 // We store the chunk size first, and align the final size on 4 bytes boundaries.
1108 // The tedious/zealous amount of casting is to avoid -Wcast-align warnings.
1109 template<typename T>
1110 struct IMGUI_API ImChunkStream
1111 {
1112  ImVector<char> Buf;
1113 
1114  void clear()
1115  {
1116  Buf.clear();
1117  }
1118  bool empty() const
1119  {
1120  return Buf.Size == 0;
1121  }
1122  int size() const
1123  {
1124  return Buf.Size;
1125  }
1126  T *alloc_chunk(size_t sz)
1127  {
1128  size_t HDR_SZ = 4; sz = IM_MEMALIGN(HDR_SZ + sz, 4u); int off = Buf.Size; Buf.resize(off + (int)sz); ((int *)(void *)(Buf.Data + off))[0] = (int)sz; return (T *)(void *)(Buf.Data + off + (int)HDR_SZ);
1129  }
1130  T *begin()
1131  {
1132  size_t HDR_SZ = 4; if (!Buf.Data) return NULL; return (T *)(void *)(Buf.Data + HDR_SZ);
1133  }
1134  T *next_chunk(T *p)
1135  {
1136  size_t HDR_SZ = 4; IM_ASSERT(p >= begin() && p < end()); p = (T *)(void *)((char *)(void *)p + chunk_size(p)); if (p == (T *)(void *)((char *)end() + HDR_SZ)) return (T *)0; IM_ASSERT(p < end()); return p;
1137  }
1138  int chunk_size(const T *p)
1139  {
1140  return ((const int *)p)[-1];
1141  }
1142  T *end()
1143  {
1144  return (T *)(void *)(Buf.Data + Buf.Size);
1145  }
1146  int offset_from_ptr(const T *p)
1147  {
1148  IM_ASSERT(p >= begin() && p < end()); const ptrdiff_t off = (const char *)p - Buf.Data; return (int)off;
1149  }
1150  T *ptr_from_offset(int off)
1151  {
1152  IM_ASSERT(off >= 4 && off < Buf.Size); return (T *)(void *)(Buf.Data + off);
1153  }
1154  void swap(ImChunkStream<T> &rhs)
1155  {
1156  rhs.Buf.swap(Buf);
1157  }
1158 
1159 };
1160 
1161 //-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1162 // [SECTION] ImDrawList support
1163 //-----------------------------------------------------------------------------
1164 
1165 // ImDrawList: Helper function to calculate a circle's segment count given its radius and a "maximum error" value.
1166 // Estimation of number of circle segment based on error is derived using method described in https://stackoverflow.com/a/2244088/15194693
1167 // Number of segments (N) is calculated using equation:
1168 // N = ceil ( pi / acos(1 - error / r) ) where r > 0, error <= r
1169 // Our equation is significantly simpler that one in the post thanks for choosing segment that is
1170 // perpendicular to X axis. Follow steps in the article from this starting condition and you will
1171 // will get this result.
1172 //
1173 // Rendering circles with an odd number of segments, while mathematically correct will produce
1174 // asymmetrical results on the raster grid. Therefore we're rounding N to next even number (7->8, 8->8, 9->10 etc.)
1175 //
1176 #define IM_ROUNDUP_TO_EVEN(_V) ((((_V) + 1) / 2) * 2)
1177 #define IM_DRAWLIST_CIRCLE_AUTO_SEGMENT_MIN 4
1178 #define IM_DRAWLIST_CIRCLE_AUTO_SEGMENT_MAX 512
1179 #define IM_DRAWLIST_CIRCLE_AUTO_SEGMENT_CALC(_RAD,_MAXERROR) ImClamp(IM_ROUNDUP_TO_EVEN((int)ImCeil(IM_PI / ImAcos(1 - ImMin((_MAXERROR), (_RAD)) / (_RAD)))), IM_DRAWLIST_CIRCLE_AUTO_SEGMENT_MIN, IM_DRAWLIST_CIRCLE_AUTO_SEGMENT_MAX)
1180 
1181 // Raw equation from IM_DRAWLIST_CIRCLE_AUTO_SEGMENT_CALC rewritten for 'r' and 'error'.
1182 #define IM_DRAWLIST_CIRCLE_AUTO_SEGMENT_CALC_R(_N,_MAXERROR) ((_MAXERROR) / (1 - ImCos(IM_PI / ImMax((float)(_N), IM_PI))))
1183 #define IM_DRAWLIST_CIRCLE_AUTO_SEGMENT_CALC_ERROR(_N,_RAD) ((1 - ImCos(IM_PI / ImMax((float)(_N), IM_PI))) / (_RAD))
1184 
1185 // ImDrawList: Lookup table size for adaptive arc drawing, cover full circle.
1186 #ifndef IM_DRAWLIST_ARCFAST_TABLE_SIZE
1187 #define IM_DRAWLIST_ARCFAST_TABLE_SIZE 48 // Number of samples in lookup table.
1188 #endif
1189 #define IM_DRAWLIST_ARCFAST_SAMPLE_MAX IM_DRAWLIST_ARCFAST_TABLE_SIZE // Sample index _PathArcToFastEx() for 360 angle.
1190 
1191 // Data shared between all ImDrawList instances
1192 // You may want to create your own instance of this if you want to use ImDrawList completely without ImGui. In that case, watch out for future changes to this structure.
1193 struct IMGUI_API ImDrawListSharedData
1194 {
1195  ImVec2 TexUvWhitePixel; // UV of white pixel in the atlas
1196  ImFont *Font; // Current/default font (optional, for simplified AddText overload)
1197  float FontSize; // Current/default font size (optional, for simplified AddText overload)
1198  float CurveTessellationTol; // Tessellation tolerance when using PathBezierCurveTo()
1199  float CircleSegmentMaxError; // Number of circle segments to use per pixel of radius for AddCircle() etc
1200  ImVec4 ClipRectFullscreen; // Value for PushClipRectFullscreen()
1201  ImDrawListFlags InitialFlags; // Initial flags at the beginning of the frame (it is possible to alter flags on a per-drawlist basis afterwards)
1202 
1203  // [Internal] Lookup tables
1204  ImVec2 ArcFastVtx[IM_DRAWLIST_ARCFAST_TABLE_SIZE]; // Sample points on the quarter of the circle.
1205  float ArcFastRadiusCutoff; // Cutoff radius after which arc drawing will fallback to slower PathArcTo()
1206  ImU8 CircleSegmentCounts[64]; // Precomputed segment count for given radius before we calculate it dynamically (to avoid calculation overhead)
1207  const ImVec4 *TexUvLines; // UV of anti-aliased lines in the atlas
1208 
1209  ImDrawListSharedData();
1210  void SetCircleTessellationMaxError(float max_error);
1211 };

1576 // Internal state of the currently focused/edited text input box
1577 // For a given item ID, access with ImGui::GetInputTextState()
1578 struct IMGUI_API ImGuiInputTextState
1579 {
1580  ImGuiID ID; // widget id owning the text state
1581  int CurLenW, CurLenA; // we need to maintain our buffer length in both UTF-8 and wchar format. UTF-8 length is valid even if TextA is not.
1582  ImVector<ImWchar> TextW; // edit buffer, we need to persist but can't guarantee the persistence of the user-provided buffer. so we copy into own buffer.
1583  ImVector<char> TextA; // temporary UTF8 buffer for callbacks and other operations. this is not updated in every code-path! size=capacity.
1584  ImVector<char> InitialTextA; // backup of end-user buffer at the time of focus (in UTF-8, unaltered)
1585  bool TextAIsValid; // temporary UTF8 buffer is not initially valid before we make the widget active (until then we pull the data from user argument)
1586  int BufCapacityA; // end-user buffer capacity
1587  float ScrollX; // horizontal scrolling/offset
1588  ImStb::STB_TexteditState Stb; // state for stb_textedit.h
1589  float CursorAnim; // timer for cursor blink, reset on every user action so the cursor reappears immediately
1590  bool CursorFollow; // set when we want scrolling to follow the current cursor position (not always!)
1591  bool SelectedAllMouseLock; // after a double-click to select all, we ignore further mouse drags to update selection
1592  bool Edited; // edited this frame
1593  ImGuiInputTextFlags Flags; // copy of InputText() flags
1594  ImGuiInputTextCallback UserCallback; // "
1595  void *UserCallbackData; // "
1596 
1597  ImGuiInputTextState()
1598  {
1599  memset(this, 0, sizeof(*this));
1600  }
1601  void ClearText()
1602  {
1603  CurLenW = CurLenA = 0; TextW[0] = 0; TextA[0] = 0; CursorClamp();
1604  }
1605  void ClearFreeMemory()
1606  {
1607  TextW.clear(); TextA.clear(); InitialTextA.clear();
1608  }
1609  int GetUndoAvailCount() const
1610  {
1611  return Stb.undostate.undo_point;
1612  }
1613  int GetRedoAvailCount() const
1614  {
1615  return STB_TEXTEDIT_UNDOSTATECOUNT - Stb.undostate.redo_point;
1616  }
1617  void OnKeyPressed(int key); // Cannot be inline because we call in code in stb_textedit.h implementation
1618 
1619  // Cursor & Selection
1620  void CursorAnimReset()
1621  {
1622  CursorAnim = -0.30f;
1623  } // After a user-input the cursor stays on for a while without blinking
1624  void CursorClamp()
1625  {
1626  Stb.cursor = ImMin(Stb.cursor, CurLenW); Stb.select_start = ImMin(Stb.select_start, CurLenW); Stb.select_end = ImMin(Stb.select_end, CurLenW);
1627  }
1628  bool HasSelection() const
1629  {
1630  return Stb.select_start != Stb.select_end;
1631  }
1632  void ClearSelection()
1633  {
1634  Stb.select_start = Stb.select_end = Stb.cursor;
1635  }
1636  int GetCursorPos() const
1637  {
1638  return Stb.cursor;
1639  }
1640  int GetSelectionStart() const
1641  {
1642  return Stb.select_start;
1643  }
1644  int GetSelectionEnd() const
1645  {
1646  return Stb.select_end;
1647  }
1648  void SelectAll()
1649  {
1650  Stb.select_start = 0; Stb.cursor = Stb.select_end = CurLenW; Stb.has_preferred_x = 0;
1651  }
1652 };

1883 // ImGuiViewport Private/Internals fields (cardinal sin: we are using inheritance!)
1884 // Every instance of ImGuiViewport is in fact a ImGuiViewportP.
1885 struct ImGuiViewportP : public ImGuiViewport
1886 {
1887  int DrawListsLastFrame[2]; // Last frame number the background (0) and foreground (1) draw lists were used
1888  ImDrawList *DrawLists[2]; // Convenience background (0) and foreground (1) draw lists. We use them to draw software mouser cursor when io.MouseDrawCursor is set and to draw most debug overlays.
1889  ImDrawData DrawDataP;
1890  ImDrawDataBuilder DrawDataBuilder;
1891 
1892  ImVec2 WorkOffsetMin; // Work Area: Offset from Pos to top-left corner of Work Area. Generally (0,0) or (0,+main_menu_bar_height). Work Area is Full Area but without menu-bars/status-bars (so WorkArea always fit inside Pos/Size!)
1893  ImVec2 WorkOffsetMax; // Work Area: Offset from Pos+Size to bottom-right corner of Work Area. Generally (0,0) or (0,-status_bar_height).
1894  ImVec2 BuildWorkOffsetMin; // Work Area: Offset being built during current frame. Generally >= 0.0f.
1895  ImVec2 BuildWorkOffsetMax; // Work Area: Offset being built during current frame. Generally <= 0.0f.
1896 
1897  ImGuiViewportP()
1898  {
1899  DrawListsLastFrame[0] = DrawListsLastFrame[1] = -1; DrawLists[0] = DrawLists[1] = NULL;
1900  }
1901  ~ImGuiViewportP()
1902  {
1903  if (DrawLists[0]) IM_DELETE(DrawLists[0]); if (DrawLists[1]) IM_DELETE(DrawLists[1]);
1904  }
1905 
1906  // Calculate work rect pos/size given a set of offset (we have 1 pair of offset for rect locked from last frame data, and 1 pair for currently building rect)
1907  ImVec2 CalcWorkRectPos(const ImVec2 &off_min) const
1908  {
1909  return ImVec2(Pos.x + off_min.x, Pos.y + off_min.y);
1910  }
1911  ImVec2 CalcWorkRectSize(const ImVec2 &off_min, const ImVec2 &off_max) const
1912  {
1913  return ImVec2(ImMax(0.0f, Size.x - off_min.x + off_max.x), ImMax(0.0f, Size.y - off_min.y + off_max.y));
1914  }
1915  void UpdateWorkRect()
1916  {
1917  WorkPos = CalcWorkRectPos(WorkOffsetMin); WorkSize = CalcWorkRectSize(WorkOffsetMin, WorkOffsetMax);
1918  } // Update public fields
1919 
1920 // Helpers to retrieve ImRect (we don't need to store BuildWorkRect as every access tend to change it, hence the code asymmetry)
1921  ImRect GetMainRect() const
1922  {
1923  return ImRect(Pos.x, Pos.y, Pos.x + Size.x, Pos.y + Size.y);
1924  }
1925  ImRect GetWorkRect() const
1926  {
1927  return ImRect(WorkPos.x, WorkPos.y, WorkPos.x + WorkSize.x, WorkPos.y + WorkSize.y);
1928  }
1929  ImRect GetBuildWorkRect() const
1930  {
1931  ImVec2 pos = CalcWorkRectPos(BuildWorkOffsetMin); ImVec2 size = CalcWorkRectSize(BuildWorkOffsetMin, BuildWorkOffsetMax); return ImRect(pos.x, pos.y, pos.x + size.x, pos.y + size.y);
1932  }
1933 };

2453 // Transient per-window data, reset at the beginning of the frame. This used to be called ImGuiDrawContext, hence the DC variable name in ImGuiWindow.
2454 // (That's theory, in practice the delimitation between ImGuiWindow and ImGuiWindowTempData is quite tenuous and could be reconsidered..)
2455 // (This doesn't need a constructor because we zero-clear it as part of ImGuiWindow and all frame-temporary data are setup on Begin)
2456 struct IMGUI_API ImGuiWindowTempData
2457 {
2458  // Layout
2459  ImVec2 CursorPos; // Current emitting position, in absolute coordinates.
2460  ImVec2 CursorPosPrevLine;
2461  ImVec2 CursorStartPos; // Initial position after Begin(), generally ~ window position + WindowPadding.
2462  ImVec2 CursorMaxPos; // Used to implicitly calculate ContentSize at the beginning of next frame, for scrolling range and auto-resize. Always growing during the frame.
2463  ImVec2 IdealMaxPos; // Used to implicitly calculate ContentSizeIdeal at the beginning of next frame, for auto-resize only. Always growing during the frame.
2464  ImVec2 CurrLineSize;
2465  ImVec2 PrevLineSize;
2466  float CurrLineTextBaseOffset; // Baseline offset (0.0f by default on a new line, generally == style.FramePadding.y when a framed item has been added).
2467  float PrevLineTextBaseOffset;
2468  ImVec1 Indent; // Indentation / start position from left of window (increased by TreePush/TreePop, etc.)
2469  ImVec1 ColumnsOffset; // Offset to the current column (if ColumnsCurrent > 0). FIXME: This and the above should be a stack to allow use cases like Tree->Column->Tree. Need revamp columns API.
2470  ImVec1 GroupOffset;
2471 
2472  // Keyboard/Gamepad navigation
2473  ImGuiNavLayer NavLayerCurrent; // Current layer, 0..31 (we currently only use 0..1)
2474  short NavLayersActiveMask; // Which layers have been written to (result from previous frame)
2475  short NavLayersActiveMaskNext;// Which layers have been written to (accumulator for current frame)
2476  ImGuiID NavFocusScopeIdCurrent; // Current focus scope ID while appending
2477  bool NavHideHighlightOneFrame;
2478  bool NavHasScroll; // Set when scrolling can be used (ScrollMax > 0.0f)
2479 
2480  // Miscellaneous
2481  bool MenuBarAppending; // FIXME: Remove this
2482  ImVec2 MenuBarOffset; // MenuBarOffset.x is sort of equivalent of a per-layer CursorPos.x, saved/restored as we switch to the menu bar. The only situation when MenuBarOffset.y is > 0 if when (SafeAreaPadding.y > FramePadding.y), often used on TVs.
2483  ImGuiMenuColumns MenuColumns; // Simplified columns storage for menu items measurement
2484  int TreeDepth; // Current tree depth.
2485  ImU32 TreeJumpToParentOnPopMask; // Store a copy of !g.NavIdIsAlive for TreeDepth 0..31.. Could be turned into a ImU64 if necessary.
2486  ImVector<ImGuiWindow *> ChildWindows;
2487  ImGuiStorage *StateStorage; // Current persistent per-window storage (store e.g. tree node open/close state)
2488  ImGuiOldColumns *CurrentColumns; // Current columns set
2489  int CurrentTableIdx; // Current table index (into g.Tables)
2490  ImGuiLayoutType LayoutType;
2491  ImGuiLayoutType ParentLayoutType; // Layout type of parent window at the time of Begin()
2492  int FocusCounterRegular; // (Legacy Focus/Tabbing system) Sequential counter, start at -1 and increase as assigned via FocusableItemRegister() (FIXME-NAV: Needs redesign)
2493  int FocusCounterTabStop; // (Legacy Focus/Tabbing system) Same, but only count widgets which you can Tab through.
2494 
2495  // Local parameters stacks
2496  // We store the current settings outside of the vectors to increase memory locality (reduce cache misses). The vectors are rarely modified. Also it allows us to not heap allocate for short-lived windows which are not using those settings.
2497  float ItemWidth; // Current item width (>0.0: width in pixels, <0.0: align xx pixels to the right of window).
2498  float TextWrapPos; // Current text wrap pos.
2499  ImVector<float> ItemWidthStack; // Store item widths to restore (attention: .back() is not == ItemWidth)
2500  ImVector<float> TextWrapPosStack; // Store text wrap pos to restore (attention: .back() is not == TextWrapPos)
2501  ImGuiStackSizes StackSizesOnBegin; // Store size of various stacks for asserting
2502 };

2504 // Storage for one window
2505 struct IMGUI_API ImGuiWindow
2506 {
2507  char *Name; // Window name, owned by the window.
2508  ImGuiID ID; // == ImHashStr(Name)
2509  ImGuiWindowFlags Flags; // See enum ImGuiWindowFlags_
2510  ImVec2 Pos; // Position (always rounded-up to nearest pixel)
2511  ImVec2 Size; // Current size (==SizeFull or collapsed title bar size)
2512  ImVec2 SizeFull; // Size when non collapsed
2513  ImVec2 ContentSize; // Size of contents/scrollable client area (calculated from the extents reach of the cursor) from previous frame. Does not include window decoration or window padding.
2514  ImVec2 ContentSizeIdeal;
2515  ImVec2 ContentSizeExplicit; // Size of contents/scrollable client area explicitly request by the user via SetNextWindowContentSize().
2516  ImVec2 WindowPadding; // Window padding at the time of Begin().
2517  float WindowRounding; // Window rounding at the time of Begin(). May be clamped lower to avoid rendering artifacts with title bar, menu bar etc.
2518  float WindowBorderSize; // Window border size at the time of Begin().
2519  int NameBufLen; // Size of buffer storing Name. May be larger than strlen(Name)!
2520  ImGuiID MoveId; // == window->GetID("#MOVE")
2521  ImGuiID ChildId; // ID of corresponding item in parent window (for navigation to return from child window to parent window)
2522  ImVec2 Scroll;
2523  ImVec2 ScrollMax;
2524  ImVec2 ScrollTarget; // target scroll position. stored as cursor position with scrolling canceled out, so the highest point is always 0.0f. (FLT_MAX for no change)

2609  // We don't use g.FontSize because the window may be != g.CurrentWidow.
2610  ImRect Rect() const
2611  {
2612  return ImRect(Pos.x, Pos.y, Pos.x + Size.x, Pos.y + Size.y);
2613  }
2614  float CalcFontSize() const
2615  {
2616  ImGuiContext &g = *GImGui; float scale = g.FontBaseSize * FontWindowScale; if (ParentWindow) scale *= ParentWindow->FontWindowScale; return scale;
2617  }
2618  float TitleBarHeight() const
2619  {
2620  ImGuiContext &g = *GImGui; return (Flags & ImGuiWindowFlags_NoTitleBar) ? 0.0f : CalcFontSize() + g.Style.FramePadding.y * 2.0f;
2621  }
2622  ImRect TitleBarRect() const
2623  {
2624  return ImRect(Pos, ImVec2(Pos.x + SizeFull.x, Pos.y + TitleBarHeight()));
2625  }
2626  float MenuBarHeight() const
2627  {
2628  ImGuiContext &g = *GImGui; return (Flags & ImGuiWindowFlags_MenuBar) ? DC.MenuBarOffset.y + CalcFontSize() + g.Style.FramePadding.y * 2.0f : 0.0f;
2629  }
2630  ImRect MenuBarRect() const
2631  {
2632  float y1 = Pos.y + TitleBarHeight(); return ImRect(Pos.x, y1, Pos.x + SizeFull.x, y1 + MenuBarHeight());
2633  }
2634 };

2736 // [Internal] sizeof() ~ 104
2737 // We use the terminology "Enabled" to refer to a column that is not Hidden by user/api.
2738 // We use the terminology "Clipped" to refer to a column that is out of sight because of scrolling/clipping.
2739 // This is in contrast with some user-facing api such as IsItemVisible() / IsRectVisible() which use "Visible" to mean "not clipped".
2740 struct ImGuiTableColumn
2741 {
2742  ImGuiTableColumnFlags Flags; // Flags after some patching (not directly same as provided by user). See ImGuiTableColumnFlags_
2743  float WidthGiven; // Final/actual width visible == (MaxX - MinX), locked in TableUpdateLayout(). May be > WidthRequest to honor minimum width, may be < WidthRequest to honor shrinking columns down in tight space.
2744  float MinX; // Absolute positions
2745  float MaxX;
2746  float WidthRequest; // Master width absolute value when !(Flags & _WidthStretch). When Stretch this is derived every frame from StretchWeight in TableUpdateLayout()
2747  float WidthAuto; // Automatic width
2748  float StretchWeight; // Master width weight when (Flags & _WidthStretch). Often around ~1.0f initially.
2749  float InitStretchWeightOrWidth; // Value passed to TableSetupColumn(). For Width it is a content width (_without padding_).
2750  ImRect ClipRect; // Clipping rectangle for the column
2751  ImGuiID UserID; // Optional, value passed to TableSetupColumn()
2752  float WorkMinX; // Contents region min ~(MinX + CellPaddingX + CellSpacingX1) == cursor start position when entering column
2753  float WorkMaxX; // Contents region max ~(MaxX - CellPaddingX - CellSpacingX2)
2754  float ItemWidth; // Current item width for the column, preserved across rows
2755  float ContentMaxXFrozen; // Contents maximum position for frozen rows (apart from headers), from which we can infer content width.
2756  float ContentMaxXUnfrozen;
2757  float ContentMaxXHeadersUsed; // Contents maximum position for headers rows (regardless of freezing). TableHeader() automatically softclip itself + report ideal desired size, to avoid creating extraneous draw calls
2758  float ContentMaxXHeadersIdeal;
2759  ImS16 NameOffset; // Offset into parent ColumnsNames[]
2760  ImGuiTableColumnIdx DisplayOrder; // Index within Table's IndexToDisplayOrder[] (column may be reordered by users)
2761  ImGuiTableColumnIdx IndexWithinEnabledSet; // Index within enabled/visible set (<= IndexToDisplayOrder)
2762  ImGuiTableColumnIdx PrevEnabledColumn; // Index of prev enabled/visible column within Columns[], -1 if first enabled/visible column
2763  ImGuiTableColumnIdx NextEnabledColumn; // Index of next enabled/visible column within Columns[], -1 if last enabled/visible column
2764  ImGuiTableColumnIdx SortOrder; // Index of this column within sort specs, -1 if not sorting on this column, 0 for single-sort, may be >0 on multi-sort
2765  ImGuiTableDrawChannelIdx DrawChannelCurrent; // Index within DrawSplitter.Channels[]
2766  ImGuiTableDrawChannelIdx DrawChannelFrozen; // Draw channels for frozen rows (often headers)
2767  ImGuiTableDrawChannelIdx DrawChannelUnfrozen; // Draw channels for unfrozen rows
2768  bool IsEnabled; // IsUserEnabled && (Flags & ImGuiTableColumnFlags_Disabled) == 0
2769  bool IsUserEnabled; // Is the column not marked Hidden by the user? (unrelated to being off view, e.g. clipped by scrolling).
2770  bool IsUserEnabledNextFrame;
2771  bool IsVisibleX; // Is actually in view (e.g. overlapping the host window clipping rectangle, not scrolled).
2772  bool IsVisibleY;
2773  bool IsRequestOutput; // Return value for TableSetColumnIndex() / TableNextColumn(): whether we request user to output contents or not.
2774  bool IsSkipItems; // Do we want item submissions to this column to be completely ignored (no layout will happen).
2775  bool IsPreserveWidthAuto;
2776  ImS8 NavLayerCurrent; // ImGuiNavLayer in 1 byte
2777  ImU8 AutoFitQueue; // Queue of 8 values for the next 8 frames to request auto-fit
2778  ImU8 CannotSkipItemsQueue; // Queue of 8 values for the next 8 frames to disable Clipped/SkipItem
2779  ImU8 SortDirection : 2; // ImGuiSortDirection_Ascending or ImGuiSortDirection_Descending
2780  ImU8 SortDirectionsAvailCount : 2; // Number of available sort directions (0 to 3)
2781  ImU8 SortDirectionsAvailMask : 4; // Mask of available sort directions (1-bit each)
2782  ImU8 SortDirectionsAvailList; // Ordered of available sort directions (2-bits each)
2783 
2784  ImGuiTableColumn()
2785  {
2786  memset(this, 0, sizeof(*this));
2787  StretchWeight = WidthRequest = -1.0f;
2788  NameOffset = -1;
2789  DisplayOrder = IndexWithinEnabledSet = -1;
2790  PrevEnabledColumn = NextEnabledColumn = -1;
2791  SortOrder = -1;
2792  SortDirection = ImGuiSortDirection_None;
2793  DrawChannelCurrent = DrawChannelFrozen = DrawChannelUnfrozen = (ImU8)-1;
2794  }
2795 };

2906  bool IsResetDisplayOrderRequest;

2908  bool IsDefaultSizingPolicy; // Set if user didn't explicitly set a sizing policy in BeginTable()
2909  bool MemoryCompacted;

2922 // Transient data that are only needed between BeginTable() and EndTable(), those buffers are shared (1 per level of stacked table).
2923 // - Accessing those requires chasing an extra pointer so for very frequently used data we leave them in the main table structure.
2924 // - We also leave out of this structure data that tend to be particularly useful for debugging/metrics.
2925 struct ImGuiTableTempData
2926 {
2927  int TableIndex; // Index in g.Tables.Buf[] pool
2928  float LastTimeActive; // Last timestamp this structure was used
2929 
2930  ImVec2 UserOuterSize; // outer_size.x passed to BeginTable()
2931  ImDrawListSplitter DrawSplitter;
2932 
2933  ImRect HostBackupWorkRect; // Backup of InnerWindow->WorkRect at the end of BeginTable()
2934  ImRect HostBackupParentWorkRect; // Backup of InnerWindow->ParentWorkRect at the end of BeginTable()
2935  ImVec2 HostBackupPrevLineSize; // Backup of InnerWindow->DC.PrevLineSize at the end of BeginTable()
2936  ImVec2 HostBackupCurrLineSize; // Backup of InnerWindow->DC.CurrLineSize at the end of BeginTable()
2937  ImVec2 HostBackupCursorMaxPos; // Backup of InnerWindow->DC.CursorMaxPos at the end of BeginTable()
2938  ImVec1 HostBackupColumnsOffset; // Backup of OuterWindow->DC.ColumnsOffset at the end of BeginTable()
2939  float HostBackupItemWidth; // Backup of OuterWindow->DC.ItemWidth at the end of BeginTable()
2940  int HostBackupItemWidthStackSize;//Backup of OuterWindow->DC.ItemWidthStack.Size at the end of BeginTable()
2941

2945  }

2974 {

2999  // Windows
3000  // We should always have a CurrentWindow in the stack (there is an implicit "Debug" window)
3001  // If this ever crash because g.CurrentWindow is NULL it means that either
3002  // - ImGui::NewFrame() has never been called, which is illegal.
3003  // - You are calling ImGui functions after ImGui::EndFrame()/ImGui::Render() and before the next ImGui::NewFrame(), which is also illegal.
3004  inline ImGuiWindow *GetCurrentWindowRead()
3005  {
3006  ImGuiContext &g = *GImGui; return g.CurrentWindow;
3007  }

3011  }

3127  // (Old) IMGUI_VERSION_NUM < 18209: using 'ItemAdd(....)' and 'bool focused = FocusableItemRegister(...)'
